#Question 1

io_income_rs %>% 
  drop_na(donor) %>% 
  group_by(donor, type_donor) %>% 
  summarise(total_donation = sum(amount_nominal, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(-total_donation) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% #this is necessary for the slice function to work 
  slice(1:10) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = reorder(donor, total_donation), y = total_donation, fill = as.factor(type_donor)))+
  geom_col()+
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::dollar)+
  labs(title = "Top 10 overall donors", x= "Donor", y= "Total donation", fill= "Type of donor") +
  theme_classic()+
  coord_flip()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'donor'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

  #How to adjust the x axis? -->

#Question 2

io_income_rs %>% 
  filter(donor== "United States") %>% 
  group_by(year, issue_area) %>% 
  summarise(total_donation = sum(amount_nominal), na.rm=TRUE) %>%    
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = total_donation)) + 
  geom_line(aes(color = issue_area))+
  facet_wrap(~issue_area, scales = "free_y")+ #make the scale change by facet
  labs(title = "US Donation by Issue Area", 
       x = "Year",  
       y = "Donation", caption = "Beware: The scale varies by issue area")
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

#Question 3

io_income_rs %>% 
  filter(year == 2000 | year == 2020) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = type_donor, y = amount_nominal, fill = type_donor)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~year)+
  labs(title = "Distribution of all donations in the year 2000 and in the year 2020",
       x= "", y="donation")+
  scale_y_log10(labels = scales::dollar)+
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2") #To make it color blind friendly

#Question 4

io_income_rs %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=amount_nominal))+ #year is a continuous factor
  geom_point(aes(shape = type_donor), alpha=.5)+ #less ink, use alpha to adjust transparency
  facet_wrap(~issue_area, scales = "free_y")+
  scale_y_log10(labels = scales::dollar)+
  geom_smooth(method="lm", color="red") #linear regression
